Resolves a target path (file or directory) to its full context chain — rollup/intent/leaf nodes — and renders them as labeled text sections for injection into an LLM prompt, with de-duplication across a session.

Missing nodes are never errors: `serve_one` substitutes a one-line `(absent: no {kind} at this level)` marker so every chain level stays visible even when sparse. Only a genuinely unreadable present file raises `CtxError::Io`. Freshness (stale/fresh/never-generated/unknown) is assessed separately per node via `freshness::assess` against hash sidecars, and rendered as an extra marker line above the body — orthogonal to presence, so a present-but-stale node shows both its content and a `[STALE …]` warning.

Key entry points: `chain_for(env, raw) -> Result<Vec<ServedNode>, CtxError>` parses `raw` (`.` = repo root, trailing `/` tolerated) and dispatches to `chain::for_dir`/`chain::for_file` depending on whether the target is a directory. `fresh_chain_for(env, session_id, raw) -> Result<Option<Vec<ServedNode>>, CtxError>` filters out node ids already recorded in the session ledger (`session::load`/`session::save`) and returns `None` if nothing left is "worth showing" — defined by `worth_showing` as present-content OR `Assessment::NeverGenerated`; plain absent markers alone don't count, since they carry no new information. This dedup logic is shared by both hook-mode and CLI-path-mode callers specifically so the same node is never re-shown by either, or by repeated calls — session state in `session.rs` is the coupling point.

`render(nodes) -> String` builds the `=== id [kind] ===` section format consumed downstream; if this format changes, anything parsing rendered output elsewhere must change too.